         <h1>Joe Slovo, a Stalinist Who Battled Apartheid, Is Dead at 68 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Joe Slovo , the Communist intellectual widely credited with being a mastermind of South Africa 's national reconciliation , died early today , his spokesman , Stephen Laufer , announced . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 68 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was cancer of the bone marrow . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Slovo , an advocate in the South African Communist Party for half a century , was a folk hero to many blacks , the first white admitted into the leadership of the African National Congress and a member of the team that negotiated the end of white rule . <br><blue>5</blue>He was Minister of Housing in the first freely elected Government of South Africa . <br><blue>6</blue>With the arguable exception of F. W. de Klerk , the President who surrendered the white political monopoly , probably no white man did as much as Mr. Slovo to shape the new South Africa . <br><blue>7</blue>And he immensely enjoyed the irony of it : that although fellow whites vilified him as a Stalinist and a revolutionary , his major contributions to the new order were acts of compromise and moderation . <br><blue>8</blue>It was Mr. Slovo , with his militant credentials as a former commander of anti-apartheid guerrillas , who in 1990 persuaded Nelson Mandela and other resistance leaders to suspend their military assaults to create a climate for negotiations . <br><blue>9</blue>And it was Mr. Slovo who in 1992 first broached the idea of a unity Government , including a five-year guarantee of job security for the powerful and potentially disruptive whites in the civil service and the military . <br><blue>10</blue>Born in Lithuania in 1926 , he moved to South Africa with his parents at the age of 9 . <br><blue>11</blue>He fought with a South African armored division against the Nazis in World War II , then used a veteran 's grant to study law at the University of the Witwatersrand , where he met a fellow law student named Nelson Mandela . <br><blue>12</blue>Mr. Slovo had joined the Communist Party in 1942 . <br><blue>13</blue>Mr. Mandela was something of a black nationalist and , as he explained in his autobiography , he disdained Communism as a foreign , white ideology . <br><blue>14</blue>But the men forged a friendship that grew into an unshakeable political alliance . <br><blue>15</blue>Over the years Mr. Slovo and other white Communists assumed influential places in the African National Congress . <br><blue>16</blue>Mr. Slovo often said his party 's greatest role was in steering the Congress away from black nationalism to a doctrine of nonracialism . <br><blue>17</blue>" The culture of nonracialism is now deeply embedded , " he said in a recent interview . <br><blue>18</blue>" That has a great deal to do with the Communist Party . " <br><blue>19</blue>Although the A.N.C. probably lost some white support for its alliance with the Communists , Mr. Mandela doggedly defended the partnership , likening it to the West 's alliance with Stalin against Hitler . <br><blue>20</blue>Even when the Communist Party was legal , Mr. Slovo was repeatedly arrested and banned from public gatherings or political activities . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>The culture of nonracialism</m_str> (17_2) 	<m_str>That</m_str> (18_2) 	<br><blue>2(3)</blue>: <m_str>the African National Congress</m_str> (15_14) 	<m_str>the African National Congress</m_str> (4_33) 	<m_str>the Congress</m_str> (16_13) 	<br><blue>3(15)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Slovo</m_str> (6_28) 	<m_str>Mr. Slovo</m_str> (15_4) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (7_15) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (7_23) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_7) 	<m_str>Mr. Slovo</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (16_5) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_24) 	<m_str>Stephen Laufer</m_str> (1_27) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (17_12) 	<m_str>Mr. Slovo</m_str> (12_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (5_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Slovo</m_str> (20_9) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_2) 	<br><blue>4(1)</blue>: <m_str>a recent interview</m_str> (17_15) 	<br><blue>5(4)</blue>: <m_str>South Africa 's</m_str> (